Durban - Police killed three men during a shootout in Loskop near Estcourt in KwaZulu-Natal and also recovered unlicensed firearms and bulletproof vests on Saturday. Captain Nqobile Gwala, police spokesperson, said members of National Intervention Unit and Tactical Response Team were deployed as part of a crime stabilisation operation, followed up on information at a house in the Ngonyameni area. “On entering the house, police officers were attacked by a group of armed suspects who opened fire on them.  Police retaliated and three suspects were fatally wounded during the shootout whilst another three were arrested at the scene,” said Gwala. Gwala also said that a police officer was shot on both legs and was taken to hospital. “Four unlicensed firearms, ammunition and bulletproof vests were recovered from the suspects. One of the deceased suspects was wanted for an attempted murder case committed in Loskop this month,” continued Gwala. Last Tuesday, police arrested four men in possession of four unlicensed firearms which include rifles, pistols and ammunition at the same house. “The recovered firearms will be subjected to ballistic tests to ascertain if they were used in the commission of any other crime in the country. Charges of murder, attempted murder, possession of unlicensed firearms and ammunition were opened for investigation. The arrested suspects will appear in the Estcourt Magistrate's Court soon,” she said. Major General Bheki Langa, Acting Provincial Commissioner in KwaZulu-Natal praised police for the recovery of the unlicensed firearms and ammunition. “Our police will defend themselves when attacked by ruthless criminals while executing their duties. We wish the  injured police official a speedy recovery,” said Langa. Daily News